<h3>Funding, partners and other acknowledgements</h3>
<p>We are very grateful to the Arts and Humanities Research Council (AHRC) and to the University of Wales for their generous support for this project over five years.</p>

<p>We have been extremely fortunate in our research partners - the National Library of Wales and the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales.</p>

<p>In addition to the many kindnesses shown by its staff during the project, we are indebted to the National Library of Wales for providing us with access to digital images from the most important manuscripts and for establishing an effective way for us to display them on our website. The Library also will be hosting our website in the long term. We would also like to thank Dafydd Evans of the Screen and Sound Archive for all his help in preparing the sound files of the poems.</p>

<p>We are grateful to Martin Crampin for his graphic design work, including the creation of a logo for the project, and for his advice on the general appearance of the two websites. Our thanks also to Nigel Callaghan for his help in creating 'Guto's World'.</p>

<p>The staff of the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales have always been very generous with their knowledge about the houses of Guto's patrons, and we must specifically thank Richard Suggett. We are also grateful for their permission to use various images for the project. It was a pleasure to collaborate with Mr Suggett and the staff of <a href="http://www.see3d.co.uk/">See3D</a> in Aberystwyth to create the animation 'Guto in Cochwillan' which is shown on 'Guto's Wales'.</p>

<p>We are also grateful to the Library of Bangor University, the Central Library Cardiff, and the British Library for their kind permission to show images from some of their manuscripts on our website.</p>

<p>The Staff of the University of Wales Dictionary have always been ready to help us, and granted us access to their important collection of unpublished slips and to their resources in general.</p>

<p>The members of the Editorial Board and the Consultant Editor have been extremely supportive during the project, in formal meetings or in replying to general queries:
